  abstract = {Interactive Dynamic Influence DiagramsÂ (I-DIDs) face a long-term standing challenge of dealing with unknown behavior of other agents who share a common environment with a subject agent in a partially observable stochastic game. A diversity-based technique provides promising solutions in a data-driven approach to I-DIDs; however, it triggers the new challenge of limited historical data of agentsâ interactions for generating potential behaviors of other agents. To tackle this issue, we propose a Generative Interactive Dynamic Influence DiagramÂ (GI-DID) framework, which integrates various generative methods and incorporates a novel perplexity-based metric to enhance policy tree ensemble diversity. Within this framework, we propose the Wasserstein Divergence Adversarial AutoencoderÂ (WDAE) for behavior generation, which diversifies and generates potential behaviors, improving modeling and prediction capabilities. Experimental results on two classic problem domains demonstrate the WDAE-based methodâs effectiveness in enhancing I-DID performance, contributing to advancements in opponent modelling and paving the way for future explorations of multiagent decision making in an open artificial intelligentÂ (AI) environment.},
