  abstract = {Driven by the latest advances in industrial artificial intelligence, automatic guided vehicles (AGVs) have been widely used for material handling in flexible workshops. In the pursuit of agile and flexible production transportation planning, the ability to handle unpredictable and dynamic events is becoming increasingly important. In order to achieve this real-time dynamic control, this study proposes a distributed multi-agent architecture to solve the dynamic Multi-AGVs scheduling problem. Double Deep Q-Network algorithm is used to train the scheduling agent, capture the relationship between production transportation operation information and scheduling goals, and make real-time scheduling decisions for flexible jobs with constant arrival intervals. Specialized state, action, and reward representations are proposed to handle variable specifications of dynamic scheduling problems. The performance of this method under different scene scales was verified through simulation studies. Numerical results show that compared with existing traditional heuristic scheduling strategies, this method not only has superior performance, but also its advantages persist even if the manufacturing system job scale changes.},
