  abstract = {Web applications are gradually becoming the main entry points for attackers to exploit vulnerabilities and launch attacks. Existing dynamic testing tools struggle to reach deep program logic because they cannot handle path constraints, while static testing tools are limited by language-specific rules and expert experience, making it difficult to effectively cover multi-language code in Web applications. To address these limitations, this paper proposes a new Web vulnerability discovery method based on Large Language Model (LLM), called VoidSight. Void-Sight adopts a novel three-stage integrated architecture. This architecture integrates Retrieval-Augmented Generation, code embeddings, and the CAMEL multi-agent dialogue framework, thereby transforming vulnerability detection from similarity matching based on static code representations into an interactive reasoning process with active information acquisition. The process first extracts 5,613 CVE records from GitHub security advisories, cleans them, and filters out key vulnerability code lines in PHP, Java, JavaScript, TypeScript, Python, and Go. Then, for each line of vulnerability code, it generates semantically equivalent code snippets in other languages and uses embedding models to match similar vulnerability lines. Finally, two agents, the âWeb Frontend Vulnerability Verifierâ and âCode Vulnerability Researcherâ collaborate to track along data flows and evaluate vulnerability exploitability. To date, VoidSight has identified 12 vulnerabilities in 8 projects on GitHub. After reporting them to developers via email and issue, we obtained 12 CVE IDs. Under the joint scanning of Semgrep, SonarQube, ZAP, and Nikto, 8 vulnerabilities were not detected},
  publisher = {IEEE},
