  abstract = {The evolution of DevSecOps Practices has enhanced organizational capacity to rollout software changes in different instances. However, the development comes with challenges in cybersecurity, as there is an increased need to identify and mitigate malware within the CI/CD pipelines. Heuristic detection and traditional signature-based approaches have become ineffective against the evolving malware landscape. Both polymorphic and zero-day threats continuously affect systems that use the traditional approaches. To advance solutions to these malware challenges, AI driven solutions are needed, ensuring that there is an accurate management of safety within DevSecOps environments. AI powered malware detection is key in ensuring accuracy, automation and speed in executing these roles. Key findings in this research indicate that the AI models have superiority in managing polymorphic and Zero-day attacks. Models such as deep learning techniques (Transformers, RNNs and CNNs) have a greater efficiency in terms of false positive reduction, detection rates and response times, leading to an incremental value for the systems. Integrating AI into the CI/CD pipelines leads to better development process, as challenges are well addressed in the course of enabling safety for all users. Nonetheless, false positives, adversarial attacks and demand for Explainable AI (XAI) still stand out as critical areas for research, which can enable future advances in the field. For organizations, this research indicates that the use of both supervised and unsupervised learning models brings in a capacity to deploy AI driven systems in real world workflows. The research finally indicates that the use of AI enabled malware detection models is key to advancing organizational safety in the CI/CD pipelines, creating safety in the software development lifecycle.},
