  abstract = {Open Source Intelligence (OSINT) pipelines are required to analyze millions of heterogeneous data items, ranging from news articles to social media posts, under strict quality attributes such as functional correctness, latency, and resource efficiency. Building on our previous Quality Attribute Workshop (QAW), Attribute-Driven Design (ADD), and Architecture Trade-off Analysis Method (ATAM) studies, this paper introduces a fourth ADD iteration that reconsiders three architectural decisions previously identified as risk points in the earlier design. First, instead of a single âmega-agent,â a set of specialized micro-agents was employed for stance detection, named entity recognition, contradiction detection, ontology enrichment, and report generation. Second, a Retrieval-Augmented Generation with Graphs (GraphRAG) layer, which manages knowledge graph triples alongside vector embeddings, has been incorporated to eliminate separate graph and vector stores and to shorten the query path. Third, a probabilistic Bloom filter that performs URL refresh operations with $\mathcal\{O\}(1)$ complexity and without generating false negatives has replaced key-value- based caches, resulting in a significant reduction in memory usage. A prototype evaluation was conducted using three datasets containing 1 million, 2 million, and 3 million URLs. The use of the Bloom filter increased the in-memory URL query speed by 10000% during runtime. The updated ATAM sessions confirmed that the previously identified risk and trade-off scenarios are no longer considered risks, thus validating that the proposed improvements significantly enhanced the system's functional suitability, performance, and resource utilization attributes. Updated ATAM sessions demonstrated that previously identified risk and tradeoff scenarios were no longer considered risks, confirming that the proposed improvements have significantly enhanced the system's functional suitability, performance, and resource utilization attributes.},
