  abstract = {Shared Decision-Making (SDM) is a collaborative process in which patients and healthcare providers jointly make medical decisions, integrating clinical evidence with the patientâs preferences and values. Although previous research has focused on SDM through decision-support tools or manual negotiations, these methods have been limited by time and cost constraints. To overcome these challenges, this study introduces an automated SDM negotiation framework using Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS) to support decision-making for both doctors and patients. The proposed MCTSAN model demonstrates superior performance across various scenarios with differing issue complexities. Notably, it maintains high overall satisfaction and reduces satisfaction disparities between patients and healthcare providers, even as negotiation complexity increases. The model typically reaches agreements within 7 to 15 negotiation rounds, effectively enhancing satisfaction and social welfare while minimizing the time and space costs associated with negotiations. This negotiation framework proves to be a valuable tool in facilitating and promoting SDM in clinical settings.},
