  abstract = {In the last years, different working groups have tried to define comprehensive and standard YANG data models, representing the devices architecture. However, not a concrete adoption of those models has happened, with clear open issues on the way. In fact, many initiatives (i.e., OpenROADM, OpenConfig and IETF) have been working to define their own data models, without any cooperation resulting in a differentiation on the model to follow by the different vendors. In addition, each vendor has performed an interpretation of the considered models, preparing a customized version. In example, considering the disaggregated optical line systems (OLS), this has led to interoperability issues, breaking the origin idea of fully vendor agnostic management and control. In this work the concept of Open Optical Software Development Kit (OOSDK) is proposed for the control of the OLS components, relying on standard and well known South Bound Interfaces to enforce a real vendorneutral control of hardware. In particular, no specific models are adopted in the communication among SDN Controller and devices, while, relying on the soft virtualization techniques (i.e., containers) a vendor specific SDN agent is adopted to control the data-plane device. A PoC has been adopted to perform the experimental validation encompassing a heterogeneous ROADM architecture including a Lumentum degree, WSSs and EDFA amplifiers.},
